us places called Sutton, named with Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English surname is also common in Ireland (Wexford, Kildare), where it has been established since the 13th century and Gaelicized as <b>de Sutún</b>.","Jewish (from the former Ottoman Empire, including Syria): unexplained.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(bi) suthentune</i> ‘(at the place to the) south of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Setton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avi, Ronit, Yossef.  French Andree, Henri, Jacques, Maryse.","Jewish (from the Ottoman Empire): altered form of   Sutton  .","English (Middlesex): variant of   Seaton  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir. Richard Sutton was born in 1178, in Holderness, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sayer Sutton, was 22 and his mother, Edith Legrose, was 20. He married Mrs. Richard Sutton in 1203, in Holderness, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1178–":"1178–Surnud","1178–Male":"1178–Surnud","1183–Female":"1183–Surnud","1207–1248":"1207–1248","1156–1247":"1156–1247","1158–1252":"1158–1252","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","1156":"1156","1252":"1252","1172":"1172","1183":"1183","1207":"1207","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnham, Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Barnham, Sussex, England","Holderness, Aldbrough, East Riding, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Holderness, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1178–":"1178–Kuollut","1178–Male":"1178–Kuollut","1183–Female":"1183–Kuollut","1207–1248":"1207–1248","1156–1247":"1156–1247","1158–1252":"1158–1252","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","1156":"1156","1252":"1252","1172":"1172","1183":"1183","1207":"1207","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnham, Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Barnham, Sussex, England","Holderness, Aldbrough, East Riding, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Holderness, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1178–":"1178–Décédé","1178–Male":"1178–Décédé","1183–Female":"1183–Décédée","1207–1248":"1207–1248","1156–1247":"1156–1247","1158–1252":"1158–1252","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1158":"1158","1178":"1178","1156":"1156","1252":"1252","1172":"1172","1183":"1183","1207":"1207","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Barnham, Westh